Equine infectious anaemia, Germany
----------------------------------
Information received on [and dated] Thu 4 Jun 2020 from Dr Dietrich Rassow, director for Animal Health and Animal Welfare, chief veterinary officer, directorate of Animal Health and Animal Welfare, Federal Ministry of Food and Agriculture, Berlin, Germany

Summary
Report type: immediate notification
Date of start of the event: 27 May 2020
Date of confirmation of the event: 2 Jun 2020
Reason for notification: recurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 29 Jun 2018
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: equine infectious anaemia virus
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, laboratory (basic and advanced)
This event pertains to the whole country.

New outbreaks (1)
Summary of outbreaks:
Total outbreaks: 1
Outbreak 1 (20-404-00001): Rodgau, Offenbach a. Main, Hessen [Hesse]
Date of start of the outbreak: 27 May 2020
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Killed and disposed of / Slaughtered
Equidae / 7 / 1 / 0 / 1 / -

Outbreak statistics [rates apparent, expressed as percentages]
Species / Morbidity rate / Mortality rate / Case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Equidae / 14.29 / 0 / 0 / 14.29
*Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction, and/or slaughter

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive

Control measures
Measures applied: movement control inside the country; screening; quarantine; selective killing and disposal; disinfection; vaccination permitted (if a vaccine exists); no treatment of affected animals
Measures to be applied: no other measures

Diagnostic test results:
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test date / Result
Hessisches Landeslabor (regional laboratory) / Equidae / agar-gel precipitation (AGP) test / 2 Jun 2020 / positive

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

